Raw dev notes -- The Deep Dive into RTL and AI Platforms

**1. Project & Why:**
Okay, so this project, `smart-hebrew-rtl`, is my attempt to make using AI chat platforms (like the big ones, you know) a lot smoother for Hebrew speakers. The goal is to intelligently apply Right-to-Left (RTL) formatting where it's needed, without messing up English content or breaking the UI. It's a browser extension, and it's been a real challenge because these platforms are constantly changing their DOM.

**2. What was done:**
This past week was a whirlwind, pushing out three versions (2.2.1, 2.2.2, 2.2.3) in rapid succession.
A huge chunk of work went into refining the core CSS injection logic. I added a "manifest CSS injection" with "retry backoff" and even a "triple-apply after streaming" mechanism. This was crucial for handling the super dynamic content on some platforms, especially one particular one that streams content in chunks. I also optimized this, realizing that not *all* platforms need the streaming CSS, so I removed it from a few to keep things lean.

A major new feature was "Deep Research RTL." This involved tackling sandboxed `data: URI` iframes, which was a beast. Initially, I tried rewriting the `src`, but that was a no-go. The fix involved injecting directly into the `contentDocument`. This opens up a whole new level of RTL support for embedded content. I also expanded the manifest to include `oaiusercontent.com` for this.

I also squashed some annoying bugs: English content getting forced RTL on one platform's AI Studio, and a sidebar navigation issue. Input fields got some love too, moving from `dir=auto` to `dir=rtl` for better consistency, and then a big win with "native keyboard control + smart input RTL" (a `unicode-bidi` fix) in v2.2.3, which is a huge usability boost.

Beyond the code, there was a ton of documentation and marketing prep. I updated `CLAUDE.md` (my internal dev notes) with all the new injection strategies and TODOs. I also spent a *lot* of time crafting social media posts for the launches, iterating through multiple drafts to focus on unique features, user benefits, and avoiding competitor bashing. Privacy policy links were added and moved around to be more visible.

And the research! I did deep dives into competitor extensions, analyzing their techniques (like `KaTeX protection`, `IntersectionObserver`, `adaptive settle logic`). I also started a market research doc to understand demand better. This involved extracting selector inventories from platforms using CDP and analyzing how other extensions handle complex DOM structures. I even set up a minified build pipeline.

**3. What was hard or surprising:**
The biggest struggle was definitely the "Deep Research RTL" feature and those sandboxed iframes. It felt like hitting a brick wall trying to get CSS into them. The `src` rewrite attempt was a dead end, and figuring out `contentDocument` injection took a lot of trial and error. It's a reminder that browser extension development often means fighting against the browser's security models in a good way.

Another surprising challenge was the sheer amount of iteration needed for the social media posts. I thought it would be quick, but getting the messaging right – balancing technical depth with user-facing benefits, avoiding competitive negativity, and ensuring it was all in Hebrew – was a mini-project in itself. It really highlighted the difference between "building it" and "telling people about it."

The dynamic nature of these AI platforms is a constant battle. The "retry backoff" and "triple-apply" mechanisms are a testament to how often elements might not be ready or might get re-rendered. It's like trying to paint a moving train.

**4. Personal Reflection:**
This period felt incredibly intense, almost like a sprint. Pushing out three versions in a few days, each with significant updates, was exhausting but also really satisfying. There were moments of pure frustration, especially with the iframe injection, where I questioned if it was even possible. But then, getting it to work, seeing the Hebrew text flow correctly in those tricky areas, felt like a huge win.

I'm learning so much about advanced DOM manipulation, browser extension architecture, and even a bit about product marketing. It's not just about writing code; it's about understanding the user's pain points, anticipating platform changes, and communicating the value. The constant research into competitor extensions and platform internals feels like detective work, which I secretly enjoy. It's pushing me to think beyond just "make it work" to "make it robust, maintainable, and truly smart."

**5. What's next:**
More advanced DOM techniques and continued platform monitoring.
